text: If anyone doesnt know, the final scene is not really optimus, its nemisis prime, his evil man-made counterpart. Optimus as shown in the trailer is in deep space searching for the creators. The beasts in the begining were not dino-bots, most likely predacons, as explained in TF:Prime. Optimus is not dead, most likely in stasis, and the Narrator is most likely King Arthur or the current US leader. The giant robot swinging the sword for one scene is most likely Megatron, as he is confirmed as Megatron (not Galvatron) and is in a new body (how is up for debate) And Mark or Bee does not die in the last scene it shows bee quickly raising his arm so he could be injured but most likely not killed (they couldnt kill Bee but who knows anymore) And to touch up on the Nemisis Prime, he could be made of Dark Energon but its not confirmed, as it could also be decepticon or human made (insert terrible TF:4 Galvatron joke here) and is most likely the main villian, except for the giant planet-type thing moving near the moon (If you know what that is please do tell id love to know). So yeah if you have anymore questions just ask and ill most likely answer, and Thx, have a good night (or day whenever your watching this)

text: After seeing this trailer, I've decided not to see this movie in theaters. I'm not saying the movie is automatically going to be terrible (who knows, they might have actually learned a thing or two) but as someone who once thought this series was pretty cool and fun, I've lost my patience. This trailer looks and sounds practically identical to the teasers for the last three films: the jump cuts, the brooding soundtrack, the brief shots of random "awesome moments", and once again, they're leading us to believe this is going to the ultimate conflict that will change everything for everyone. Well, the last three entries didn't change squat, and considering Paramount already has a Bumblebee spin-off film AND an official sixth entry planned for 2018 and 2019, I think it's safe to say this movie will do nothing but give the fans what they want. That's all very well and good for them, but until the filmmakers give us a real game-changer (like, I dunno, give Bee his damn voice back or something) this franchise is dead to me.

text: To everyone debating on wether or not That"s really Optimus at the end, it is. In the comics and Cartoons Optimus ventures out on his own just like he did at the end of Transformers 4. In the comics, he runs out of energon and becomes dosile and frozen. The Quintessons ,which are the creators of the transformer race, eventually run into him and bring him back to life, but  not before re-programming to do there wishes. So Optimus is not neccesrily evil now, hes just programmed to do what ever they want. He does get glimpses of his core autobot tho, which is why he says "forgive me" in the trailer. Also, if you think unicron has something to do with prime being evil, you are wrong. At the end of the last transformers movie Prime says hes coming for his creators and he wont stop till he finds them. Im pretty  sure Bay is sticking to that direction for this movie

text: This franchise could be so much more than what it is. It could have actual themes, such as, politics/ war/ good vs. evil. The possibilities are endless for the transformers. Spin-off movies to focus on individual characters, or guardians of the galaxy-like adventure movies set in deep space. Also who wouldn't want to see a prequel set during the autobot/ decepticon war. We as an audience are ready to accept these robots as actual relatable characters with emotions. And yet every time they make these things they seem to just take a step to the side instead of a step forward. Maybe it's Michael Bay's fault, or maybe the studio has figured out what makes money and has told him to only make that. All I'm saying is, give these characters the movie they deserve.

text: Ugh... I saw a whole lot of human characters here like usual, and also like usual, not that many bots. Also, did they really go for a Nemesis Prime story arc yet keep him with his standard red and blue coloring!? Like all the prior TF films I will give this one a chance, but it's not looking good... The first film was pretty great, and the second one was pretty bad. Then DOTM was a solid return to form which actually became my personal favorite from the series. But then they release AOE which was a horrible film with some of the worst pacing I've ever seen. Given the inconsistency in these films, this one is an absolute coin toss. The silver lining here is that it would be tough to make a film worse than AOE, so at the very minimum Last Knight should be a slight improvement compared to that nightmare of a film.

text: So let's list out everything we know ( from the plot summary and set visit)  or think is in this movie so far:  - how the Transformers were formed (  Lorenzo di Bonaventura also mentioned origins of Cybertron) - the origins of the autobot-decipticon rift - di Bonaventura also teased that we‚Äôll be exploring the history of the Primes - Transformers Reaction Force {TRF}- a military group led by Santos that is trying to eradicate all of the Transformers, regardless of their affiliation - Colonel Lennox and the mystery of where his true loyalties lie  -Cade hiding autobots from the TRF -Cade on the run with Isabela Moner's teenage character (she has an autobot scooter named Squeaks) - a submarine Transformer and an underwater sequence with Lennox and his men - Megatron's return -Nazis and Winston Churchill - King Arthur  - evil Optimus -Dinobots (and mini dinobots) - other humans: Stanley Tucci, Tyrese Gibson,  John Turturro , Laura Haddock, and  Anthony Hopkins -the creators Optimus went looking for? -F-ing Unicron? (Don't forget a probable romance plot, Bumblebee and the other autobots, and whatever McGuffin Micheal Bay is making the Deceptions ad Autobots fight over this time.)  Did I miss anything?  So for all of you saps getting overhyped again please stop; I made the same mistake with the trailers for Age of Extinction. You're setting yourselves up for disappointment. This will be the worst and most muddled Transformers movie yet; look at everything that we know and think is going to happen. The worst part is that it will somehow still gross 1 billion dollars. WHEN this movie gets under 30% on Rotton Tomatoes don't say no one warned you.   ( If I'm wrong, I 'll happily eat crow because I actually want to see a Transformers movie that is good again.)

text: The trailer is always better than spending 3hrs in a cramped chair that is a theater with people that may be annoying. Where is our God saving us from the EVIL Decepticons. Decepticons that is a cool word. Just break it down and see why that is an awesome name for a EVIL bunch of machines that Transform from one object to another. Some even do more than 1 transformation. Sky Scream - It is a male Android, a gun, and a fighter jet.(yes details are short). the real reason why these movies do so well is because they can be played in multiple countries around the world and they don't have to really change anything except for the language. text: I never thought I'd say this, but this trailer is actually really good. Think about it, we got a great cast, there looks to be a coherent plot, the main female character doesn't seem to have been Michael Bayified, the music was pretty good, the action looks really cool, there wasn't any Michael Bay humor... Could this actually be the first *good* Transformers movie? While I think the first one was ok, it's still not a very good movie. But this has a lot of potential, and while the other Transformers trailers also looked cool, none of them have been as good as this one. And besides, this film has Anthony Hopkins in it, what could go wrong? Well ok, a lot of things could go wrong looking at Michael Bay's filmography and his track record. But my main reason as to why I think this film could be great is because Michael Bay could be turning into a better director, if you watch his latest film 13 Hours, you will be surprised at how good it is. With that film, it looked as if Michael Bay was actually *trying* to make a good film. And it worked, because it was actually really good. Seriously, the man hasn't made a good movie since The Rock (Very underrated). But this year he's actually been doing pretty well as a director and as a producer: 13 Hours was really good, TMNT 2 was bad but not nearly as terrible as the original, and the Ouija prequel turned out to be great. What I'm trying to say is that I genuinely think this could be great, and I *hope* it is. Sorry for the long comment. #HopeforMichaelBay #HopeforTransformers

text: What a god awful dumpster fire. First that screech is sop distracting it's hard to focus on the mess thats happening on screen.  I could barely focus on any dialogue because of that, it's basically the 'scratching your nails on the blackboard' version of the Inception "Bwoam".   Also why is it so hard to make a trailer that doesn't give away the plot?  The film takes place in the future, Optimus has left and once again theres a small band of autobots trying to survive against what appears to be security drones designed to wipe them out.  Optimus is in space frozen, and most likely gets found by the planet thing, which I know is Unicron even though I really don't want it to be and he's turned evil by it or is at least controlled by it.   Optimus and Unicron (seriously, thats the look they're going for? I just threw up a little)  come back to earth and they have to fight to stop him.    Basically 75% of the plot points of the film are in that trailer including Optimus attacking them.  Whats wrong with leaving a surprise for your audience anymore?  Why does everything have to be revealed in the trailer now?    Did you see the Force Awakens trailer last year?  That is a text book example of how to create and build interest in your film without giving to much away or have loud noises constantly interrupt it.

text: The Information and some theories that might be true: now in the trailer we see shocking things, first off, I'm making this because I see so many people's attention on bumblebees death and this comment will tell them what may be REALLY GOING ON. SO here are the question I am answer these questions: What in the world is that giant planet that looks like it's about to eat the moon?! My answer: There can be only 2 answers. 1. Unicron is here. 2. New cybertron made by the creators of Optimus? My best answer would be Unicron, because we know that Unicron is a massive planet eater and that planet really seems like it's next tasty meal is the moon. But IT COULD BE CYRBERTRON! Because I have never knew about anything of a planet spreading its self to piece and sort of spreading them around the planet, and eat it? But it's might be Unicron! The 2nd question: Optimus died and came back to life but ATTACKED BUMBLEBEE AND MIGHT HAVE KILLED HIM?! And why did he say "forgive me..."? My answer: We see that in the beginning he is dead, all out of energon (for those of you that don't know what energon is, it is the blood of all transformers and how they stay alive) but Optimus was deep in space... how is he back? Only one answer: Unicron. Unicron must've found Optimus and brought him back to life, but in the end he attacked bumblebee?! The second answer that applies to the first: OPTIMUS IS CORRUPTED! Now I know what some of you might think, "ITS NEMESIS PRIME!" It's not. As at the end we look into his eyes and they seem purple. If you have not watch the transformer shows or games, Dark energon brings transformers back to life, but either zombified (sorta) or under Unicrons control. OPTIMUS IS NOT ZOMBIFIED BUT INFECTED under control by Unicron! For those of you who watch Transformers Prime, Unicron was controlling Megatron setting a goal to bring him back. But failed. In the movie Unicron is using Optimus! But I don't know the reason why, it is maybe because Optimus can kill the transformers since he has great power or Optimus could be the only one... or is there another...? Which brings to the next question, 1:38 1:48 WHO IS THAT BADASS LOOKING DECEPTICON OR AUTOBOT?! My OFFICIAL AND TRUE ANSWER: now don't get me wrong on who this is. ITS Megatron or Galvatron because now all of you would be like "Megatron or Galvatron doesn't use a sword! He doesn't use a shield!" Well in the 4th movie Galvatron says: "we shall meet again prime... FOR I AM REBORN." But! He might no longer be a Decepticon! He walked away in the jungle and must've found the ship where Optimus got his sword and where Cade got his alien gun. Galvatron must've claimed a sword, a shield, and A new look! Maybe armour? Who knows! But in 1:38 his eyes were red, and in 1:48 his eyes were grey-ish or blue-ish, GALVATRON IS BECOMING GOOD?! In 1:48 Him and Cade seemed to be making a deal, but it was on Cade, he seemed like Cade wanted Galvatron to help stop Unicron or stop Optimus or both. Also, since when did Galvatron knew how to use a sword? Well, it's kinda obvious, the ship must've never been found where Optimus got his sword, and Galvatron must've had enough time to train himself. Now he is prepared to face Optimus or Unicron. Another thing "The Last Knight" Galvatron could be The Last Knight? Or Optimus? Or another unknown Transformer!

text: Okay here is my official breakdown of the trailer: In the beginning, we see knights riding into battle, and then a giant dragon transformer. I'm not sure who the dragon robot is, but from the looks of the knight riding alongside the dragon, i can make two predictions about it. 1; the dragon is making a deal with the knight, similar to how lock-down made a deal with the agent from the previous movie, or 2; The dragon is a depiction of dragons from famous myths and stories about a knight slaying a dragon, and thats what the knight is doing. We continue with more flashbacks to previous wars, most likely having something to do with the fact that the transformers have been here since the birth of mankind, and that these wars were really between man and machine. Okay lets continue to the crashed satellite and the children. This will most likely happen later in the movie, with satellites falling from space because of the planet-monster thing (possibly Unicron?) The children were probably caught in the crossfire of the great battle happening between the decepticons and the autobots. Moving on to the child and the dying autobot. Im not yet sure who the autobot is but it looks like a friend to the child. The giant hole thing is most likely the planet monster that has yet to have been identified. Prime is in outer space. The man goes over the rune which is most likely an insignia from the knights we saw first in the trailer. Next we see the child again with everyone's favorite robot squeeks, who is an autobot. This covers the first quarter of the trailer, let me know if you would like a further analysis! P.S: Sorry that this is so long, there was a lot to cover

text: LMAO GEKKO'S FROM METAL GEAR SOLID 4 1:28   So I don't know what to say. I actually had high hopes for this film after how bad "Dark of the Moon" and "Age of Extinction" were. They lacked the soul and essence of Transformers. Honestly I loved the first film and viewed it as a *gasps* "masterpiece" for a number of reasons. Many may disagree but I was blown away. It took my breath away and gave me a feeling that was up there with Star Wars when I first saw it. All the special effects, unique direction. The film was literally art. For all the flaws the "Revenge of the Fallen" had. I found that the film was actually better on the 2nd and 3rd watch. I was angry with how they treated Megaton, but it didn't go full out of character like the other two films.  Personally I feel like I could write a much better film than the latest couple films, though I can't direct worth shit. Honestly Micheal Bay is horribly wrong about one thing. I believe he claimed that he could never make a film that focuses just on the Auto-Bots because without the humans in the film there would be no humanity or any way for the audience to connect with the characters. He is so wrong. The fans connected to the Transformers in the shows and the comics because they had more personality and depth to their characters. A deeper story for us to delve into. This is one of his huge fallacies. He can easily create a film both connecting us with the Transformers and still have his big action moments. Personally I would think about either making the series two or three trilogies with each film in the trilogy being a major story arc with a trilogy theme and beats to connect it as a whole. That wouldn't even fill half the content.   Trilogy One: Transformers Trilogy Two: The Beast Wars Trilogy Three: Beast Machines (this could probably be done in one or two films tbh)  Seriously Bay, you can do better. There is so much vision to behold with this series.

text: Optimus prime most likely killed some one that had dark energon and was to close and was inffected.   Info on dark energon....The violet-glowing Dark Energon supercharges any Transformer who ingests it, making them stronger, faster, more powerful...and more aggressive. It turns pain into pleasure, rendering any blows inflicted on a user futile and heals their wounds as well. However, it also acts as a powerful narcotic, filling the user with thrilling, dark sensations and causing addiction. Dark Energon withdrawal turns the user into a raving brute desperate to do anything for more. If the craving is not satisfied, the user devolves to a beast-like state and eventually dies. Those who imbibe Dark Energon have been seen to project it from their bodies for various destructive purposes, such as attacking enemies, overloading computers, and bringing machines under their control. When a user is killed, the energy acts like a sentient thing (a worrying aspect for a force originating from Unicron) and flies from their corpse to empower any other user nearby.  And no it is not a copy of optimus or any other Transformer due to the fact that optimus says "forgive me" before taking a swing at bumblebee.

text: I actually want Bumblebee to die (coming from a huge Transformers fan).  The character is *SO* overrated and I am kind of getting sick of him stealing all the limelight.  This would be one of the greatest things to do.  Also factor in how much people have become emotionally attached with him and we could have a brilliant scene that pulls on everyone's heart strings thus providing a excellent emotional scene for fans of the films and the character.  Take "Transformers Prime" for example.  The scene where Bumblebee dies is (imo) the best emotional scene we got.  When we as fans saw that unfold a lot of us started to cry.  Why? because the show had done such a good job of developing the characters and giving fans a reason to attach their feelings with them that when it actually happened we couldn't help but let it out. Something else I don't think these people realize is that he will come back from death (knowing Hasbro) and be renamed as Golbug/Goldfire.

text: The plot for the fourth movie was Lockdown to capture Optimus Prime and bring him to the creators (Unicron and Primus), which obviously meant they were going to use him for something. Optimus at the end of the film then goes on a search to find them, and we find out in this trailer that he is adrift in space, but that doesn't mean that he didn't find them. Optimus's purple eyes could explain that he may be under the influence of Dark Energon, which is the emanation of Unicron (which means that it was sourced from Unicron), Dark Energon can corrupt transformers as well as increase ones power, This is a reasonable theory to suggest that he found 'The Creators'. Or ya know, its Nemesis Prime and what I said goes out the window.P.S Galvatron as the good guy?!, now that would be interesting.

text: _'To Punish and Enslave'_ -- Probably the best moment in any of the TRANSFORMERS live action movies.  It looks like they intend to _'kill'_ Optimus Prime... again.  That is always a mistake.  Y'know, they've never explained, that I noticed, why it was that the AUTOBOTS had to do a hard re-entry to crash land on Earth in the first movie.  Maybe this flick will explain where they were, and why they were somewhere, out there, in space, orbiting Earth to begin with...?  I would have expected they could have just landed their ship on Earth instead.  Meh.  Mostly I accept that there are going to be tremendously huge, gaping holes in the plots of these movies, that are designed to look _'AWESOME!'_ more than anything else and have been labeled, quite appropriately I think, as _'EXPLOSATHONS'_.  Basically?  Any storyline or dialog that is presented is just there to fill the space between explosions.  And who doesn't like explosions?

text: I'm a bit torn with the theories. On one hand, Optimus could in fact be infected with dark energon. But then on the other hand, this Prime could be Nemesis Prime. Let's see...   Dark Energon theory: Maybe Optimus never made it to the "Creators" and instead ran out of normal Energon, that's why we see him floating aimlessly in space. This could have possibly led him to drift off toward an unknown area of space and he's picked up by, dare I say his name, Unicron. The Devourer of Worlds takes control of Optimus and sends him back to Earth to do some bad deeds.   Nemesis Prime theory: Optimus does in fact make it to the "Creators," battles them to the best of his ability but he ultimately loses. Because they want him back (Lockdown reference), they send a copy or clone, of Optimus back to Earth where the copy can lay down some hurt on the humans, Autobots, and Decepticons all together without having to stain their own hands.   Idk it took me two days to really think this through~

The thing at 1:15 might be some kind of probe from unicron to dig him out or Primus. And throughout the trailer they're a ton of cybertronian 'structures' being unearthed, The scene at 1:40 shows the hexagonal pattern much like Cybertron has, and at the very end Optimus has purple Dark Energon infused eyes and are fighting in some kind of massive access port which I suspect will be leading to Unicron.   The scene with Optimus fighting Bumbleee I suspect is near the end/middle. They're trying to head into the earths core to stop Unicron from waking up and 'shaking the earth off' much like Transformers Prime. text: a grittier, more pessimistic feel for this one would be very welcome. i'd even be okay with them killing off bumblebee, but if they kill optimus again, no one believes that he'll stay dead. to be fair, he died and resurrected multiple times before the bay movies, but still, overused is overused. if there is a significant death here, it needs to be permanent. if killing off one of the transformers would be too limiting, then kill off one of the main human characters... and i mean MAIN characters, for good.  overall, the transformers bay movies have been... sub par in character development, had relatively basic plots, had a few too many cringey moments early in the series... but for all their flaws, the fight scenes looked really, really good. in the other areas, they've been improving slightly, but i have to admit that the character development is still subpar.  give us something unexpected. if the "good guy's" achieve their goal, make them actually PAY for it, make us feel their loss. maybe have them fail altogether... or better yet, make us question who the bad guy really is. this new evil optimus... maybe give him a reason for his changing sides beyond simple "i got corrupted by this glowy purple energy, now i'm the bad guy." make him have a point for his actions, make us, the viewers, question right from wrong.

text: I will add my two cents. I believe that the three-headed dragon is Scourge who holds the jungle planet Animatron, which I think is the planet we see overtaking the moon and reaching Earth. It would actually tie into the theory of Unicron coming up soon in the films. I also think that Optimus has been affected by Dark Energon which is why his eyes are purple and he is fighting against the Autobots. I think the little girl's significance is that the Autobot that she was leaning against and looking at as he was down is her protector. Similar to Bumble Bee and Sam (Shia LaBeouf). I believe that the Decepticon walking @ 1:38 is Galvatron who is now Megatron, since he took over.   EDIT: Also @ 1:51 we see Optimus Prime's eyes turn back to blue, which strengthens the theory that he was possessed by Dark Energon.  That's all I can gather from my point of view. It seems believable to me.

text: So, a while ago I was watching an old g1 episode titled, "Dark Awakening". In the episode, a dead Optimus Prime is reanimated by the Quintesons to destroy the Autobots. That seems to be the case here, which is an explanation for the theory that OP died while facing the creators in the new movie (hence seeing a frozen Optimus floating in space). Now, people may be thinking, "well they might just be that similar," seeing as how they are both inside the universe, but here is proof. In the g1 episode, a seemingly good Optimus says, "Forgive Me", before attempting to kill Hot Rod. This is the same here, with bumblebee. Hot Rod survived in the episode, and if the two continue to be linked might mean that Bumblebee might survive in what we see.

text: This needs an epic reboot. Michael Bay's version of transformers needs to be tossed. The writing and dialogue sucked for the first 4 films.¬†Sure the cartoon was no better when it came to intellectual¬†and well thought out script and plot, but it was for kids. What is Bay's excuse for ruining the franchise? Oh that is right, you make more money selling to the masses who have an average intelligence and short attention span. Insert more explosions and endless fight scenes here (along with transforming sound effects CheShishoowhooo)_______________!!!!!¬†¬†¬†Just a few things I would have done differently. 1.Omega Supreme (smarter version) would be involved. 2.Teleportation rings that opened a reasonably small gateway for travel back to Cybertron, would exist. ¬†3.The Quintessons would be discovered. 4. The script¬†would include more lines and dialogue between the Transformers and way less from the Humans, including less major human roles. I swear rich people everywhere paid their way onto the movie, just to have a small bit that was completely unneeded and drew away from the main plot.¬†5. Put action in it, but not to the point where it is just stupidly haywire. 6. Place the arc on earth, under a mountain. 7. Show that the other prime's consciousness is still in the matrix, along with all of their knowledge and show how the matrix, creates a stronger version the transformer holding it. text: Think about it. These movies make so much money. Save for the first one, the next 3 were terrible (Dark Of The Moon had *some* cool moments, but still...-_-). Just imagine how much of a success this film would be if it was actually GOOD. I don't want to lose hope in this franchise, but I've been down this road before having watched his other trailers. Let's not front. We all know this will be a stinker that looks good at first glance. And yet, we're still going to go see it and this movie will still make millions.  Michael Bay,  either you're an evil genius or you just don't care.

text: So, I managed to pause it at just the right time and you can clearly see Bumblebee's hand catching Optimus's just before the seemingly final blow near the end of the trailer. Makes me somewhat hopeful that this isn't the end of Bumblebee. Also, I haven't read or seen everything regarding this trailer but, I haven't seen anyone mention anything about the fact that Optimus's eyes change their color from blue to purple during the scenes we see him fighting Bumblebee. Could this indicate he's being controlled by Unicron or something along those lines?  And, when he says "forgive me", that could have been taken from anywhere in the movie and just stuck into the trailer at that point to make it seem like Optimus was in control of himself. It isn't like that haven't done that kind of stuff in trailers before.

text: This has tones of the Transformers animated movie. Unicron, the ultimate transformer, finds one of the faction leaders adrift (was Megatron originally) and upgrades him into being his servant so he can come after the Matrix of Leadership, which is on earth. Both sides fight each other, and the big bad, and a lot of good guys get wrecked, but ultimately one of the lesser Autobots takes over possession of the Matrix, kicks ass, and becomes the new leader of the Autobots. I can see them melding this into the new movie, but making Bumblebee the new Ubermech in the story, since someone is going to have to put OPtimus down at the end, if things go as they seem. The animated movie is actually quite good, if youre into transformers, or Anime, or Weird Al (yes, Weird Al Yankovick is in the movie) so I would recommend revisiting the original.

text: OK! Lets be straight... Michael Bay and Hasbro have FUCKED UP Since day one... The first film was Great, but each one has gone downhill since as they forgot what the whole Transformers series is about - ITS A TWO HOUR TOY COMMERCIAL!  That said, The trailer has managed to do something that NONE of the other shave managed to do... Its actually got my interest!  God when will Hasbro get it together though? TMNT 2: Out of teh Shadows is NOT a great movie by any means... But I watched it the other night and its enjoyable!!! Its enjoyable because its stays true to what it is - An Extended Toy Commercial! Nothing about that film is serious... Its a total Joke and thats what it should be!!!  The same should be true of Transformers... In fact, Even while Watching this trailer, I came up with a Treatment for 4 Movies that would stay true to the original Cartoon while at teh same time making a great Michael Bay Action Epic... But BE A TWO HOUR TOY COMMERCIAL as long as Hasbro REMEMBERS WHAT KIDS LOVE ABOUT TOYS! (Yeah Hasbro, Those One Step Flip Changers - F**K OFF!)  Will this be a Good Film... Well, its going to be action packed, I know that... Will I see it... Yes, My Son will never forgive me if I don't... Will its be what we are all hoping for....  Simple answer... NO! But at least it has caught my interest!

text: I don't get why everybody never liked Transformers. Always complained that the first movie was too focused on the humans and hardly a storyline. The storyline was clear and simple if you paid attention. Sam's great great grandfather discovered Megatron. The Allspark was actually the storyline as his glasses held the key to the Allspark. Megatron and the decepticons were going after it, so how is that not a good storyline? Even in the cartoons, the Transformers was always about the Autobots trying to save the human race and quite frankly, that's why it was more focused on the humans, so if you can't explain how the movie didn't meet your expectations, I don't wanna hear anymore than what I already explained here

text: Might I quote Carl Sagan here:  "Look again at that dot. That's here. That's home. That's us. On it everyone you love, everyone you know, everyone you ever heard of, every human being who ever was, lived out their lives. The aggregate of our joy and suffering, thousands of confident religions, ideologies, and economic doctrines, every hunter and forager, every hero and coward, every creator and destroyer of civilization, every king and peasant, every young couple in love, every mother and father, hopeful child, inventor and explorer, every teacher of morals, every corrupt politician, every "superstar," every "supreme leader," every saint and sinner in the history of our species lived there-on a mote of dust suspended in a sunbeam.  The Earth is a very small stage in a vast cosmic arena. Think of the endless cruelties visited by the inhabitants of one corner of this pixel on the scarcely distinguishable inhabitants of some other corner, how frequent their misunderstandings, how eager they are to kill one another, how fervent their hatreds. Think of the rivers of blood spilled by all those generals and emperors so that, in glory and triumph, they could become the momentary masters of a fraction of a dot.  Our posturings, our imagined self-importance, the delusion that we have some privileged position in the Universe, are challenged by this point of pale light. Our planet is a lonely speck in the great enveloping cosmic dark. In our obscurity, in all this vastness, there is no hint that help will come from elsewhere to save us from ourselves."  ~Carl Sagan, The Pale Blue Dot

text: A dragon transformer in the medieval era, I smell a transformers prime being put in this chimeric, Frankenstein, smelting pot. And going for a humans vs the alien machine angle at least Bay didn't turn Unicron into a smoke cloud or a giant female transformer with giant tits(assuming it is Unicron and not Primus or Cybertron itself). But the overall problem is that the transformers film franchise in of itself is the story is all over the map, most of the human characters are either idiots or stereotypes, and the plots seems secondary where as the special effects, fights, and explosions are primary granted it's Michael Bay expecting any real story from him is like expecting a snake head fish becoming an alge eater.  Basically the whole film franchise is an identity crisis it's too adult for kids to enjoy and yet the "comedy" is too childish for adults to tolerate, and the story is horrendous, the allspark being some magic mulligan which does whatever Bay wants it to do such as giving life to non cybertronian technology, killing and resurrecting other transformers, and giving cybertronian knowledge to organic life forms yet unable to read the language despite being edowed with cybertronian knowledge. And there's the whole decepticons working with humans thing in the third and fourth film, why on earth would any sane species side with one faction that's against organic life rather than the side that want to save that species from extinction.

text: What everyone here needs to realize is that what's happened to Optimus Prime is what he was on his way to becoming anyway so I don't think it's a big deal! Think about it. From the beginning, the largest theme IMHO of this series is the utilitarian vs. Kantian ideologies (with the latter being held by Prime in all of his incarnations as well as in the first movie). Galloway was supposed to embody the former in TF2 and it was supposed to be a great clash of ideals between him and Prime until TF2 totally dropped the ball with it! Then Optimus, and even the Bayformers fans, started to become hypocritical thanks to the third and fourth movie (the latter most of all), as OP himself leans closer and closer to the other spectrum. None was more evident when Cemetery Wind and KSI (both arguably taking up the Kantian role) tried to put an end to the whole war, all the suffering, and all the loss in AoE when they tried to destroy both factions themselves--they did have the motivation after all since most of their loved ones were lost in the Battle of Chicago, making them not so unsympathetic IMO. It'll be nice to see that continue in this film with the TRF taking up CW's role and the fact that one of the main characters, Izabella, was orphaned from the Battle of Chicago (which spawned CW and in turn the TRF). However, whereas Optimus would've usually found a way to resolve the tensions and conflict between his team and these desperate human groups in Age of Extinction, he has now instead fully tipped over to the other side of that ideology in TLK, none more evident when he says "For my world to live, yours must die." So all in all, even though he may have ended up controlled by these Creators, he was still on his way to this mindset anyway.

text: Saw this movie. SPOILERS below...      The movie was an improvement over the last one, but not as good as the first one. The movie revolves around the descendant of Merlin who is the only one to hold the staff that combines both Cybertron and Earth. Nemesis Prime is a thing, even if only for 5 minutes of screen time. Unicron is hinted at throughout the movie and is finally said at the end by "The Creator" in a post credit. WW2 is a 10 second long scene that involves Bumblebee "winning the war". The movie is long, but visually satisfying (like every other Transformers movie- the reason why people see them). The ending contains possibly the largest "WTF is going on" moment with a battle occuring on Cybertron (with Transformers and Humans) as it is crashing down over Stonehenge with a dogfight happening overhead. Nonetheless, I enjoyed it. Check it out!

text: This is an honest review of transformers the last knight: Regardless of what the critics say, which in fact is a pile of horseshit, this movie wasn't so bad as what they made it out to be, in fact, it may well be my favourite transformers yet. 2Hrs and 30mins of transformers lore, action, comedic scenes and generally great scenes which were enjoyable to watch. Many people may complain that this movie has too many explosions and the storyline is rubbish. If that's your opinion, fine, but it's wrong, simply because this movie is one of the 5 movies that actually has a proper storyline and an opener for the movies to come. This movie isn't a 15% stated by Rotten Tomatoes, it's a solid 70%.

text: Now that ive seen the movie this trailer leads you to imagine a far different movie a more serious transformers with a deep story. But nah this one was a mess with so many plot holes and subplots it should've been 2 movies. They screwed up with unicron and quintessa which foesnt explain those ships at the beginning of the 4th movie. Nemesis prime was a let down the action was little and happened to fast and zippy to register as all the transformers movies. Mark wahlberg being the last night was dumb even tho mark is awesome the movie was as if someone put a bunch if trailers together for 2:30 hours and min. But I'm not hating I'm just saying in this day in age in this era of cinema with movies from marvel, action from john which and mad max, visuals like interstellar etc. Transformers can do way better. Again I'm not hating I love these movies they are entertaining especially the first 2. So I'm just saying its my opinion tho cuz at the end of the day we just wanna see some awesome robots beat the crap out of eachother and transform but I'm just saying I could make them better haha

text: These films, not just because of money (despite performance of The Last Knight), are reaching to a close now. With Unicron in the idea of TF6, this is basically the 2nd to last film of the mainstream franchise since there is most likely no more films that could continue the storyline after Unicron enters out of the Earth. Good or bad, I appreciate how the films have went through so much to reach a concluding point for everybody, new or old, Transformers fans to watch. With The Last Knight, we see how the films will close to an end and make an Oscar-Worthy visually pleasing voyage for the 6 mainstream films. I honestly can't wait for what could be Transformers: Rise of Unicron in 2019.

People watch em consistently, starting to love the movies, and then suddenly, a lot of changes will be added to the movies??? So sad to know that especially the movie tranformers (the first three parts) already captured my heart and interest. I'm just so sad to accept some changes. text: What really killed this movie (and honestly the rest of the planned bayformers movies before the reboot) was the fact that it promised something it didn‚Äôt deliver on. The marketing showed us we would have an interesting arc of Optimus being the bad guy, the possibility of Megatron now fighting Optimus as a GOOD guy. And on top of that we were gonna learn why the transformers were here for so long. And what was planned for the future. But instead, we got a half baked sequel, the same tacky plot points. Barely any decent fight scenes. And a very rushed final product. The marketing totally promised something else, and it did not deliver.

text: If I was the screenwriter for the film, or at least the script doctor, I would have this in a way be similar to the first. It's a small story, about a young human's relationship with a Transformer, in a large universe which is recovering from the aftermath of war with the Transformers.   The first act, we get a good amount of time setting up who the girl is and how much she cares about her specific Transformers and maybe a glimpse that she's looking for a family. The inciting incident is maybe about how Megatron or someone abducts the tiny Transformer because he has something important like a message or a map to the creator of the Transformers (I believe they called her Proxima or something). This starts act 2.  In Act 2, this is where we meet Cade or maybe we meet him earlier but she goes up to him after a previous and brief meeting and asks him to help her get her Transformer back.   This leads to all of the action stuff we see in the trailers, gives a tangible reason for Cade and the girl to be around each other, ties in the whole side story with Optimus, and provides some heart to the story. I think it just connects a little better. Bay's movies are rarely boring but almost all of them, specifically the Transformers films, have so much potential.
